Basic necessities
Globally, women enterprises comprise about a third of all enterprises and contribute significantly to employment generation and development. Women are Africa’s engine: they maintain 90 per cent of the informal economy; they produce 80 per cent of the food; they support more than 40 per cent of the basic necessities of the continent's families and significantly contribute to peace (FAO).
The facilitation of women entrepreneurs to participate more in wealth creation goes beyond increasing household incomes to reduce poverty and seeks the growth of entrepreneurship for job creation and economic development.
In Kenya, as in many other African countries, the expansion of the informal sector and of self-organised and independent enterprises is, in large part, created by women whose collaborative, self-help and traditional practices and initiatives in production and trade are a vital economic resource.



