When they gain access to and control over capital, credit, technology, training and other resources, women significantly increase production, marketing and income for sustainable development.
In Kenya, women account for about 56 per cent of all entrepreneurs in the country according to the Kenya National Bureau of Statistic, 2006.
However, research indicates that there is very little connection between researchers and institutions that implement and advocate for women's economic empowerment.
The importance of evidence for policymakers will help them focus on what works to drive decision making for women’s economic empowerment.
The University of Nairobi, in collaboration with Bill and Melinda Gates, therefore, wants to focus on providing cutting edge research to policymakers and implementors to influence decisions, and upscale already existing programs.
For instance, access to government procurement opportunities which is globally rated as one of the best policies. 
