Tremendous responsibilities
Women’s experience with the Constitution review process indicates that laws, legislations, regulations and policies can drive change. This leads us-the multi-disciplinary team of researchers at the University of Nairobi to focus on three main areas.
They are; Affirmative Action Funds and Women’s Entrepreneurship, Women in Formal and informal employment, and Child Care and Women's Work. 
The last of these areas of focus is chosen because of the tremendous responsibilities that women have in taking care of children as well as having time for their businesses or employment.
The change in gender norms becomes important for this research. Policy advocacy, interaction with the policymakers, working together with civil societies and women's organisations becomes important if we are to unlock the potential for women economic empowerment.
Women’s economic empowerment as a process increases women’s right to economic resources and their power to make decisions to benefit themselves, their families and their communities.
This requires equal access to, and control over economic resources, assets, opportunities and long-term changes in social norms and economic structures that benefit women and men equally. 



